Documentation:
This report covers the Meow machine, the first entry in the Hack The Box (HTB) Starting Point series. While even simpler than Fawn, it establishes the fundamental workflow of "Scan, Identify, and Connect" using one of the oldest (and least secure) protocols in networking: Telnet.
1. Executive Summary

The Meow machine serves as an introductory exercise in identifying open ports and utilizing weak credential sets. The target was found to be running a Telnet service on port 23. Due to a critical misconfiguration, the root account was accessible without a password. This allowed for immediate administrative access to the system, leading to the retrieval of the flag file.
2. Enumeration and Reconnaissance
2.1. Connectivity Test

Initial verification was performed using the ICMP protocol to ensure the target was reachable over the VPN tunnel.

    Command: ping -c 4 <target_IP>

2.2. Port Scanning

An Nmap scan was conducted to identify active services. Since Meow is a Tier 0 machine, we focus on the most common ports.

    Command: nmap -sV <target_IP>

    Discovery: Port 23/tcp was identified as open, running a Telnet service.

2.3. Documentation and Help

To verify available options for scanning and connection tools, we can invoke the help menu from the terminal.

    Command: nmap -? or telnet -?

    Note: Using the -? flag is a quick way to view syntax without opening the full manual (man) page.

3. Exploitation: Telnet Authentication Bypass

Telnet is a terminal emulation protocol that, unlike SSH, transmits data in cleartext. On this specific target, the "root" user—the most powerful account on a Linux system—was not protected by a password.
3.1. Connection Steps

    Initiate Connection: telnet <target_IP>

    Username: When prompted with meow login:, the username root was entered.

    Password: When prompted for a password, the field was left blank and Enter was pressed.

    Access Granted: The system provided a root shell prompt (root@meow:~#).

3.2. Flag Retrieval

With administrative privileges, the system was searched for the flag:

    Command: ls (revealed flag.txt)

    Command: cat flag.txt

